### Reputation Point Table — Updated

| Action | Points | Notes |
|--------|--------|-------|
| **Edit accepted — minor** (typo, formatting, <50 chars changed) | +2 | Auto-classified by character delta |
| **Edit accepted — substantive** (new analysis, case synthesis, ≥50 chars) | +5 | The substance of legal scholarship |
| **Generic upvote received on a contribution** | +1 | Shows community agreement. Low but non-zero. Prevents gaming through friends upvoting. |
| **"This Helped Me" endorsement received** | +10 | Rare, deliberate utility signal. Much more valuable than a generic upvote. |
| **Scholar Star received** (peer-awarded recognition) | +15 | See new section below |
| **Peer review completed** (structured, rubric-based) | +3 | Rewards curation work |
| **Peer review aligned with community consensus** | +2 bonus | Builds reviewer calibration |
| **Discussion contribution cited in closing summary** | +5 | Your argument was persuasive |
| **Flagged issue subsequently resolved** | +2 | Tagging is genuine contribution |
| **First contribution by someone you mentored** | +5 | Rewards mentoring pathway |
| **Node you contributed to advances a quality tier** | Proportional | Points based on authored content in scored sections |

**Why generic upvotes get +1 (not zero):**

You raised this point and you're right. A generic upvote means "I agree with this edit" or "this looks correct to me" — it's a form of community validation, just a weaker one than "This Helped Me." Giving it zero points dismisses it entirely; giving it +1 acknowledges the signal without making it a primary driver. A contributor would need 10 generic upvotes to equal one "This Helped Me" endorsement — that ratio feels right.

**Key constraint**: A user can only upvote a specific contribution once. Self-upvoting is not possible. Upvote patterns from the same user-pair are monitored for voting ring detection (per the Mazloomzadeh fraud taxonomy research).

